      "playtime_at_review": 49908,
      "review_text": "[b]Edit 21 March 2026[/b] The monetization has only become more egregious and pay to win. Banner ads will block gameplay, New features are balanced around buying all of the packs. The weird part is a lot of new content is requiring constant [b]active[/b] gameplay, to the point where it is not really even an enjoyable [b]idle[/b] game.\n\n[h1]Feels cobbled together[/h1]\nThere are some key pain points I've noticed which make it harder to recommend this game, despite my love for idlers. Two of the major ones tend to come from the monetization system, and the UI.\n\n[h2]Feels Pay to Progress[/h2]\nFrom a very early point, it feels like the game pushes you toward paying for convenience, and for access to more meaningful progression. Best stats? Purchased. Extra Teleports? Purchased. [i]Playing more skilling minigames?[/i] [b]Purchased.[/b]\n\nThe game also has occasional banner ads in game for different content packs that you can't close out, you have to slowly wait for it to fade away. It just feels like it has TOO many monetization \n\n[h2]GUI is a mess[/h2]\nI may be a bit picky here, but it feels like there is [b]zero[/b] consistency across any of the interfaces, menus, activities, etc. Even something as simple as the button to close out of a menu is vastly different or even nonexistent in some cases. I want to run through and just update them all to match!\n\n[h2]Required Multiplayer[/h2]\nFor an idle game, I was surprised by the amount of quests / content where it is [i]required[/i] to play with others. This may be more of a personal thing, but I don't generally want to trek to third party sites to get random people to help me out in an [b]idle[/b] game. Optional activities like the dungeons, sure it is fine. Quests where you quite literally just drag another person to a random spot on the map to type something in chat? Poor design.\n\n[hr][/hr]\n\nI am going to continue playing and hope it grows on me more, but I don't know if I could recommend for someone to pick it up fresh. IdleOn doesn’t feel poorly made—it feels under-curated, like a dozen good ideas were never unified into a cohesive experience.",
      "timestamp_created": 1767819206
    },
